O-O 20. Be7 Re8 21. Bd6 Rb7 $15) (7. Bc4 Be7 $132) 7... h6 8. Bh4 ({Compared
to the relevant variation in the Najdorf here Black has the more active Nb8-c6
on the board and this is immediately telling after, let us say} 8. Bxf6 $6 Qxf6
$15) 8... Be7 9. Qd3 (9. Bf2 O-O $132 {[%cal Ge6e5]}) 9... e5 $1 {A concrete
shot at equality.} ({A typical Rauzer situation arises after} 9... g5 10. fxg5
Ng4 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bg3 hxg5 13. Be2 Ne5 14. Qd2 Rb8 15. O-O-O Qa5 16. Kb1
$14) 10. Nxc6 (10. fxe5 Nxe5 $132) 10... bxc6 11. fxe5 ({Double-edged is} 11.
f5 O-O 12. O-O-O Rb8 $5 ({another tempting opportunity is} 12... d5 13. Bxf6
Bxf6 14. exd5 Qb6 $132 {Landes - Norchenko, ICCF email, 2017}) 13. Bxf6 Bxf6
14. Qxd6 Qb6 15. Qa3 Rb7 $132 {[%cal Gf6e7]}) 11... dxe5 12. Qxd8+ Bxd8 13. Bc4
{A logical continuation.} (13. Bg3 Bc7 {leaves open the question about whose
pawn structure is better}) ({The practice has seen} 13. O-O-O Bg4 $1 14. Re1
Ba5 $1 ({a natural improvement upon} 14... Nd7 15. Bxd8 Rxd8 16. h3 Be6 17. Na4
Rc8 18. Re3 $14 {Susla - Ploscaru, LSS email, 2019}) 15. Re3 Bb6 (15... Nh5 16.
Na4 Nf4 $13) 16. Rd3 Ke7 17. h3 Be6 $11) 13... Bg4 ({A sound alternative is} 
13... Ke7 $5 14. O-O-O Be6 {, neutralizing the pressure along the a2-g8
diagonal and preparing the activation of the second bishop as well.}) 14. h3
Bh5 15. g4 ({White would definitely like to have a rook on the d1-square and
he can choose between the text for forcing ?h5 back and trading it by} 15. Be2
{A possible reaction is fearless} g5 $1 16. Bg3 Bxe2 17. Kxe2 Bc7 18. Rad1
Ke7 $11 {and the king will once again feel comfortable on the e6-square. The
exposed f5-square cannot be exploited, for White must at first think about the
security of his central pawn.}) 15... Bg6 16. O-O-O Nxe4 {A direct approach
for further simplifications, thus solving the fate of ?g6 once and forever.
More complex, albeit fully playable, is the sally} (16... Ba5 $5 {with
approximate equality again, as shown by:} 17. Bxf6 (17. Rd6 Bb4 $1 18. Rxc6
Bxc3 19. Rxf6 (19. bxc3 Bxe4) 19... gxf6 20. Bd5 Bxb2+ 21. Kxb2 Rb8+ 22. Ka1
Ke7 23. Rf1 Rb6 24. Bf2 Rb5 25. Bh4 Rb6 $11) 17... gxf6 18. Rd6 Ke7 19. Rhd1
Rhd8 20. Rxc6 Rxd1+ 21. Kxd1 Bxc3 22. bxc3 Rd8+ 23. Ke2 Bxe4 24. Ra6 Rd7 $11)
17. Rxd8+ Rxd8 18. Bxd8 Kxd8 19. Bxf7 Bxf7 (19... Nxc3 20. Bxg6 Ne2+ 21. Kd2
Nf4 22. Be4 Kc7 $11) 20. Nxe4 Bd5 21. Re1 h5 $11 *

